{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500633"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:15:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:15:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1655"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1655"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.03,0.66,0.11,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1655"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108955"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1655"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1655"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91325"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"100"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1949"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7484"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40355"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108955"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old woman presents to the anaesthetic clinic for pre-operative assessment. She was recently diagnosed with T2, N1, M0 oestrogen-receptor negative carcinoma of her right breast and is scheduled for surgery followed by radiotherapy. She has a medical history of a deep venous thrombosis following a leg fracture several years ago but no other significant medical history. She does not take any regular medications, having ceased hormone replacement therapy upon diagnosis. She has two adult children and her BMI is 29 kg/m\u00b2. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her initial investigations reveal normal full blood count, electrolytes, and coagulation studies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate thromboprophylaxis strategy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence rivaroxaban immediately as outpatient","Commence aspirin when radiotherapy begins","Commence prophylactic enoxaparin during hospitalisation","No prophylactic anticoagulation required","Commence daily aspirin immediately"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECancer patients have an increased risk of venous thromboembolism due to the malignancy itself and cancer treatments. The approach to thromboprophylaxis depends on the clinical setting and individual risk factors. Current guidelines recommend different strategies for hospitalised versus ambulatory cancer patients. This patient\u0027s history of previous deep venous thrombosis further increases her baseline thrombotic risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence prophylactic enoxaparin during hospitalisation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate approach. All cancer patients undergoing surgery or hospitalisation should receive thromboprophylaxis with low molecular weight heparin unless contraindicated. This patient will require prophylaxis during her surgical admission and any subsequent hospitalisations, particularly given her cancer diagnosis and previous venous thromboembolism history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence rivaroxaban immediately as outpatient\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate. Rivaroxaban is not used for surgical prophylaxis except in specific orthopaedic procedures such as hip or knee replacement. Prophylaxis is only required preoperatively in this case, not as ongoing outpatient therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo prophylactic anticoagulation required\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as cancer patients undergoing surgery have a clear indication for thromboprophylaxis during hospitalisation, regardless of their baseline ambulatory risk. Her previous deep venous thrombosis history makes this approach particularly inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence aspirin when radiotherapy begins\u003C/strong\u003E is not evidence-based. Aspirin is not recommended for venous thromboembolism prophylaxis in cancer patients, and radiotherapy alone does not typically warrant thromboprophylaxis unless other risk factors are present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence daily aspirin immediately\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as aspirin lacks efficacy for venous thromboembolism prevention in cancer patients and does not address the specific thrombotic risks associated with malignancy and cancer treatments, particularly in someone with previous venous thromboembolism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cancer patients require thromboprophylaxis during hospitalisation and surgical procedures due to increased venous thromboembolism risk.","Low molecular weight heparin is the most common thromboprophylaxis agen used in most settings."],"references":["Bauer K. Risk and prevention of venous thromboembolism in adults with cancer. In: Leung LK, Tirnauer J, editors.;\u200bUpToDate. [Internet]. Waltham (MA): UpToDate Inc; 2021. [updated 2020 Dec 07; cited 2021 Mar 15]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/risk-and-prevention-of-venous-thromboembolism-in-adults-with-cancer#H783126885"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91325"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1655"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91325"},"attribute